ocialist period, Kant for Children troubled the Nazis. They banned Friedlaender’s work. Rebecca Hanf, friend of Ernst Marcus, the philosopher who claimed to have resurrected Kant, recognized that Friedlaender’s Kant for Children could counter the Nazi appropriation of Kant and realign Kant with egalitarianism and anti-fascist politics, meaning the book has contemporary relevance in light of an international resurgence of fascism. A lifelong student of Kant’s works, Friedlaender deserves a wider audience among Kant scholars and students. This first English translation includes an introduction to Friedlaender as well as essays by Paul Mendes-Flohr, Sarah Holtman, Robert Louden, Kate Moran, Krista Thomason, and Jens Timmermann. For translating and editing Kant for Children, Bruce Krajewski received The 2023 Silvers Grant for Work in Progress from the Robert B. Silvers Foundation. The Robert B. Silvers Foundation is a charitable trust established by a bequest of the late Robert B. Silvers, a founding editor of the New York Review of Books, with the aim of supporting writers in the fields of long-form literary and arts criticism, the intellectual essay, political analysis, and social reportage.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aEthik. 4aFriedländer, Salomo. 4aKant, Immanuel. 4averbotene Bücher. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh  aFriedlaender, Salomo.  aKant, Immanuel.  abanned books.  aethics.1 aFriedlaender, Salomo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoltman, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrajewski, Bruce J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrajewski, Bruce James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrajewski, Bruce Jame